snippet.textDisplay: I don't know why I watched this. This channel used to be interesting plot holes and examining bad villain plots, but now it's just full of so much demonstrably untrue nonsense that it just leaves me shaking my head, at myself, because what did I expect? I guess Marvel should take it as a compliment that so much reaching has to be done to pad out the running time. The teachers are funny. Peter is a genius, but also a teenager, and therefore an idiot, and it's the mixing of the two that makes him such a great character. Mysterio is hilarious after the reveal, as Jake Gyllenhaal impersonates the most prima donna moments from every director he's ever worked with. Ugh. I'm disappointed in myself.

snippet.textDisplay:
Not to be that guy, but that bus scene was more physically accurate than you put it. It’s not a question of momentum (mass * velocity), but rather one of inertia (Newton’s First Law), “An object in motion stays in motion...” Since both Peter and the bus were originally moving at the same horizontal velocity, when Peter jumps up from the bus, it would make sense for him to continue moving at the same horizontal speed as the bus. The only reason that he would not have landed in the same position would be if the bus suddenly accelerated while he was mid air, or if a strong gust of wind hit Peter when he was outside of the bus. As long as the bus maintained a constant velocity throughout, Peter would land in the same place.

It’s kinda like how someone can juggle while in a car/train/vehicle without dropping stuff as long as the vehicle doesn’t make any jerking motions or speed up/slow down


,..that’s just my two cents

Tower Bridge, not London Bridge! But it's an easy mistake, hell con artists have 'sold' Tower Bridge claiming it was London Bridge too.
London Bridge is not as fancy looking, hence Tower Bridge is the one most people know. London Bridge is half a mile further down the River Thames. And of course they were visiting The Tower of London, hence the vault used by Hobby, and of course Tower Bridge is named because of its proximity to The Tower of London.
